2. Suitable graph of the mean BMI (BMI not body_mass weight_in_kg/height(m2)) of female and male penguins. (Assume the height is the flipper length) (5 marks)

In[]:
# Drop rows with missing values
penguins_df = df_penguins.dropna(subset=['flipper_length_mm', 'body_mass_g', 'sex'])

# Calculate BMI
penguins_df['BMI'] = penguins_df['body_mass_g'] / (penguins_df['flipper_length_mm'] ** 2)

# Calculate mean BMI for each sex
mean_bmi_df = penguins_df.groupby('sex')['BMI'].mean().reset_index()

# Plot the mean BMI for each sex using seaborn
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.barplot(x='sex', y='BMI', data=mean_bmi_df)
plt.title('Mean BMI of Male and Female Penguins')
plt.xlabel('Sex')
plt.ylabel('Mean BMI')
plt.show()

Convince the museum board

The Firehouse Museum claims they ran an event in 2014 that brought an incredible number of visitors, and that they should get extra budget to run a similar event again. The other museums think these types of events aren't that important, and budgets should be split purely based on recent visitors on an average day.

To show the museum board how the event compared to regular traffic at each museum, create a suitable chart that shows how the number of visitors to each museum evolved over time. (4 marks)

In[]:
#Your solution here
# Convert the 'Date' column to datetime format
df_museum['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df_museum['Date'])

# Set the 'Date' column as the index
df_museum.set_index('Date', inplace=True)

# Plot the number of visitors to each museum over time
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))
for column in df_museum.columns:
    plt.plot(df_museum.index, df_museum[column], label=column)

plt.title('Number of Visitors to Each Museum Over Time (2014)')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Number of Visitors')
plt.legend(title='Museum')
plt.show()

What did you observe from the graph? (2 marks)

Your answer here

  • There is a noticeable spike in visitor numbers at the Firehouse Museum around March and May 2014. This indicates that the event they hosted during this period significantly increased their visitor traffic compared to other months.
  • The other museums display relatively steady visitor patterns over the year, with some minor fluctuations but no significant spikes like the Firehouse Museum. This indicates a consistent baseline of visitor traffic for these museums.
  • The graph clearly shows that the special event hosted by the Firehouse Museum was highly successful in attracting visitors, leading to a significant increase in their numbers compared to regular traffic.

Why did you choose this type of graph? (2 marks)

You answer here

  • Line charts are particularly effective for showing how data changes over time. In this case, we want to observe the number of visitors to each museum throughout 2014, making it easy to identify trends and patterns over the months.
  • Line charts provide a clear and concise way to display data trends. They make it easy for the museum board to quickly understand how visitor numbers evolved over the year and to see the differences between regular traffic and event-driven traffic.

## Your solution here
# Melt the dataframe to have 'Year' and 'Country' as separate columns
melted_gas_prices_df = gas_prices_df.melt(id_vars=['Year'], var_name='Country', value_name='Gas_Price')

# Plot the gas prices for each country over all years using seaborn
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 10))
sns.lineplot(data=melted_gas_prices_df, x='Year', y='Gas_Price', hue='Country')

plt.title('Gas Prices for Each Country Over the Years')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Gas Price (in USD)')
plt.legend(title='Country', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
plt.show()

Is there anything interesting observed from the plot/graph? (1 mark)

Your answer here

  • Most countries show a general upward trend in gas prices over the years, indicating an increase in gas prices globally.
  • Italy and France consistently have some of the highest gas prices compared to other countries.
  • South Korea and Japan show more fluctuations in gas prices, indicating potential volatility in their gas markets.
  • Germany shows a sharp increase around the early 2000s, which could be due to policy changes or economic factors.

Why did you choose this type of graph? (2 marks)

You answer here

  • Each countrys data is separated into individual subplots. This avoids the clutter and overlapping lines that can occur in a single line chart with many countries, making it easier to see the trends for each country.
  • It is ideal for handling and visualizing multiple categories (countries, in this case) within the same dataset. It provides a comprehensive view while keeping the visual representation clean and interpretable.
  • This type of plot helps in highlighting both global patterns (e.g., general trends in gas prices) and local variations
